  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment (v0.5 synthetic)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2). Validation evidence is reported using Pearson correlation coefficient and R² between predicted and measured normalised hemolysis index values across the five flow-speed operating points; these metrics characterise agreement in trend and proportional variance but do not directly quantify the relative hemolysis index (RH) prediction error against the RH < 1 acceptance criterion required by the COU.",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/morrison-cpb-hemolysis-rh-criterion",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cou1-worst-case-identification",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/morrison-cfd-hemolysis-centrifugal-pump",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-experimental-hemolysis",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-cfd-mesh-ensemble-mrl2"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-pearson-nhi-correlation",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pearson correlation of normalised hemolysis index across operating points",
      "description": "Pearson correlation coefficient r = 0.97 was computed between CFD-predicted normalised hemolysis index (NHI) values and the corresponding in-vitro measurements at all five flow-speed operating points. The high correlation indicates that the model captures the rank ordering and proportional variation of hemolysis across operating conditions, providing strong evidence that the simulation correctly tracks relative trends in blood damage. This metric is widely used in pump hemolysis literature and is considered a standard indicator of model fidelity for hemolysis prediction studies."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-r2-nhi-fit",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "R² goodness-of-fit for normalised hemolysis index predictions",
      "description": "Coefficient of determination R² = 0.94 was obtained by regressing predicted NHI against measured NHI over the five operating points, confirming that 94% of variance in measured hemolysis is explained by the CFD model. The regression slope (0.98) and intercept (0.003) are close to the ideal 1:0 line, suggesting minimal systematic bias in the NHI magnitude. Because R² captures both trend and proportional magnitude, the assessment team concluded that the model's predictive capability for hemolysis is well-characterised and sufficient to support the worst-case identification decision."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-rmse-nhi",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "RMSE of normalised hemolysis index",
      "description": "Root-mean-square error of 0.0041 g/100 L (normalised units) was calculated across the five operating points, representing approximately 3.2% of the mean measured NHI value. The low RMSE supports the conclusion that average model error is small relative to the measurement range. Combined with the Pearson r and R² results, the validation team determined that the CFD model meets the required accuracy level for trend-based hemolysis assessment under MRL 2."
    }
  ],
